{{Infobox basketball biography | name = Carlos Yates | image = | image_size = | position = [[Forward (basketball)|Forward]] | height_ft = 6 | height_in = 5 | weight_lb = | birth_date = | birth_place = | death_date = August 13, 1989 (aged 27) | death_place = [[Washington, D.C.]] | nationality = American | high_school = [[Flint Hill School|Flint Hill]] ([[Oakton, Virginia]]) | college = [[George Mason Patriots men's basketball|George Mason]] (1981–1985) | draftyear = 1985 | career_start = | career_end = | years1 = | team1 = | highlights = * Co-[[Colonial Athletic Association Men's Basketball Player of the Year|ECAC South Player of the Year]] (1983) * 4× First Team All-ECAC South (1982–1985) * ECAC South Rookie of the Year (1982) }} '''Carlos Yates''' (died August 13, 1989) was an American [[college basketball]] player for [[George Mason University]].
==College career== Yates began his collegiate career at George Mason and played for the [[George Mason Patriots men's basketball|Patriots]] all four years. He was the [[Eastern College Athletic Conference]]'s (ECAC) Rookie of the Year in 1982 and its Co-Player of the Year in 1983 (along with [[James Madison Dukes men's basketball|James Madison]]'s [[Dan Ruland]]). He was selected to four straight All-ECAC South Conference First Teams from 1981 to 1985. In addition, Yates earn honorable mention [[All-America]] honors those four straight years.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://umterps.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/harrington_joe00.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2009-12-30 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223090427/http://umterps.cstv.com/sports/m-baskbl/mtt/harrington_joe00.html |archivedate=2008-12-23 |df= }} Joe Harrington - Player Bio</ref> On January 31, 1983 during Yates's sophomore season, he was selected by [[Sports Illustrated]] as their National Player of the Week.<ref>[https://archive.is/20130102064434/http://vault.sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1120475/index.htm Player of the Week SI Vault]</ref>
Yates is George Mason University's all-time leading scorer in men's basketball history with 2,420 points<ref name=heraldjournal>{{cite news|title=Former college hoop star shot and killed|work=[[Spartanburg Herald-Journal|Herald-Journal]]|agency=Associated Press|date=1989-08-16|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=jqYeAAAAIBAJ&sjid=LM4EAAAAIBAJ&pg=4458,138049&hl=en|accessdate=2012-05-30}}</ref> as well as the state of Virginia's fourth all-time leading scorer.<ref name=VASID>[http://www.gmu.edu/org/vasid/VaSID-records/VaSID-rec-mbb-D1.htm Virginia State Basketball Records]. Retrieved on June 21, 2008.</ref> He also holds the school record for career [[field goal (basketball)|field goals]] made and attempted and [[free throws]] made and attempted.
==Professional career== Yates was drafted fourth overall by the Florida Suncoast Stingers in the 1985 [[Continental Basketball Association]] draft.
==Death== Yates was shot and killed on August 13, 1989 near [[Robert F. Kennedy Memorial Stadium|Robert F. Kennedy Stadium]] in [[Southeast, Washington, D.C.|southeast]]<ref>{{cite news|title=Ex-hoop star shot to death|work=[[The Bulletin (Bend)|The Bulletin]]|agency=Associated Press|date=1989-08-15|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=9ZBTAAAAIBAJ&sjid=yYYDAAAAIBAJ&pg=5843,1203873&hl=en|accessdate=2012-05-30}}</ref> [[Washington, D.C.]]<ref name=heraldjournal/>
