{{about|relatives of suicide victims|people who have survived their own suicide attempts|suicide attempt}}
A '''suicide survivor''' or '''survivor of suicide''' is one of the family and friends of someone who has committed [[suicide]].<ref name="bryant">{{cite book|title=Handbook of Death & Dying|editor=Clifton D. Bryant|editor-link=Clifton D. Bryant|publisher=[[Sage Publications]], Inc.|location=Thousand Oaks, California|date=2003|volume=1: The Presence of Death|page=345|isbn=0-7619-2514-7|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3z9EpgisKOgC&pg=PA345 |accessdate=11 December 2011}}</ref>

Given the social stigma associated with suicide, suicide survivors are often unable to cope with their loss and [[grief]] using normal support systems, and are "forced into a privatized and individualistic mode of grieving," making the healing process even more difficult.<ref>{{cite book|last=Pisón|first=Ramón Martínez de |title=Death by despair: shame and suicide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XqLyPFFUtesC&pg=PA60|year=2006|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=978-0-8204-6382-7|page=60}}</ref>

Estimates are that for every suicide, "there are seven to ten people intimately affected".<ref>{{cite book|last=Lukas|first=Christopher|author2=Henry M. Seiden |title=Silent Grief: Living in the Wake of Suicide|publisher=Jaron Aronson|location=Northvale, New Jersey|origyear=1987|year=1997|page=5|isbn=0-7657-0056-5}}</ref>

